column1: 135077;instagram;2018-11-26 06:02:50;FALSE;"@regran_ed from @narcissist_free -  have you ever called a narcissist out on his or her behavior? if so
column2: then you know they won‚Äôt tolerate the truth very well at all. brace yourself for one of the coldest
column3: worst and possibly most explosive episodes you've yet to see.

column1: when i finally figured out the narcissist and told him so (although at the time i did not know what a narcissist was and could not put a name to it) he withdrew. he found a new supply and pursued her and there began the process of a brutal discard
column2: the likes of which i had never experienced.

column1: i had been beaten up twice in my life by two other men at two different times in my life: by my father and later by my not-yet-husband. this discard was worse than either of those two beatings.

column1: 135171;instagram;2018-11-25 23:53:33;FALSE;"i am here for you. i see you. darkness and light are no longer held in different spaces but dance in the same.

peru was magical. in so many different ways. in peru i found myself in the darkness that i feared to explore. allowed myself to play in my insecurities and see them for what they were. stories. stories that exploded once embraced into shining stars that filled the galaxy that is me.
the light i surrendered to emerged from my being. beamed both through the top of my head and the the bottom of my feet. connecting me with pachamama and the star beings.
grandmother ayahuasca and my great leader @janeislistening  led me into the unknown. myself. guided me to discover the beautiful masterpiece that i covered with chaos.

i danced in the galaxy and cried from the depth of my soul. i surrendered to the light and shadows of myself and fell in love with my life. this vessel i chose is amazing. adorable and beautiful. i love me and i love you.

column1: many of my loved ones have come forward to me out of fear of what to do or how they just felt hopeless. as i listened to each one and gave them a place a shoulder to cry on and in some cases resources to go to. as ive listened to their stories with different circumstances they all came back to the similar questions regarding their self worth if they are enough? let me first just tell you if you are being abused i believe you! and you are not at fault or alone. you are more than enough for being just you and we all love you. don‚Äôt let anyone tell you other wise. it‚Äôs the person who didn‚Äôt see what an amazing person you are and decided it was okay to mistreat you. no matter what mistakes you have made you do not deserves to be mistreated or punished for them . you deserve to walk the streets or in your home safely and feel loved. ***************************************************
we need to continue this conversation with the ones around us and change our views on gender based violence.

‚ùå‚Ä¢stop coming from a judgmental point of view and stop asking why this person is still there or with that person? why they are doing what they are doing? questions that question their self worth or parenthood. making assumptions about other people or placing them where we think they need to be instead of asking them what they need causes more hurt than healing. ‚Ä¢üî•let us start by asking ourselves why the person is choosing to use power over another person? how can we help? how can we make a difference? ‚Ä¢üî•be supportive friend or family member and be a listening ear to the one who is battling an incredible painful situation what are they in need of at this point in time? and walk beside through their journey >>>‚ùå‚Ä¢violence is a serious human right violation.  let‚Äôs stand shoulder to shoulder with survivors

column1: 135469;instagram;2018-11-25 22:20:55;FALSE;"i‚Äôve had a lot of men in my life this year. .

column5: handymen. it‚Äôs been many many many. i would say that 50% of them have listened
column6: worked honestly and diligently and have been above and beyond amazing. .

column1: others have done things they probably don‚Äôt even process as weird‚Äîlike asking for my husband‚Äôs name so he can pay the bill. or talking down to me telling me what i want is not really what i want. or saying sexually explicit things
column2: or one even yelling at me and stealing over $500 worth of goods that i paid for.  i was talking about it to a friend last night and she told me an electrician came into her apartment and immediately deadbolted the door behind him. it sent her into a mild panic. luckily
column3: he didn‚Äôt mean anything by it‚Äîbut still just an example of how little he understood about what we women go through every time we let someone into our space.

column1: women close to me have been shot
column3: and killed by their husbands in a fits of anger and insanity (one was murdered in her church parking lot back in 2011). when i was teaching inner city school in florida i was punched by a large student and almost assaulted. so when any man yells at me or makes me feel unsafe‚Äîit‚Äôs not ok. .

column1: this year has been super vulnerable for women as i think we have all told stories we haven‚Äôt shared for years and maybe forever. stories of #metoo and #believewomen are hard
column2: but we have to keep speaking out about these things. we have to end the silence even in a world that feels like its ignoring our voices at every turn.

column1: and while none of my construction work has been too bad
column2: there have been multiple times that the interactions have made me feel stupid
column6: and vulnerable. always within the walls of my own home. and i usually end up blaming myself for not being outspoken enough or knowing the right words or if i just knew more about construction maybe it would all be better.

column1: for all the men who make me feel safe i love you. for all the women who are daily using their voices to speak up

column1: 135507;instagram;2018-11-25 21:48:03;TRUE;;"posted @withrepost ‚Ä¢ @3tokenbrowngirls a quick breakdown because it seems like a lot of our followers are confusing these two concepts. you can be whyte and still struggle from day 1. it happens. but that doesn't negate whyte privilege nor does it mean you struggle the same as poc.
examples of whyte privilege that struggling whyte folks might benefit from (over poc) but not notice:
- landlords giving you a bit more leeway if you're late on your rent
- banks more likely to give you a loan with a lower interest rate
- being much less likely to be profiled and attacked when on the streets
- getting more help/support for mental and physical health problems
- having family members financially help you in times of crisis
- school systems/teachers offering more support to your kids
- getting treated better/not followed in stores
all of these things are out of your control. i get that
column2: and understand that you aren't doing it on purpose! but that does not mean it doesn't happen. acknowledging these things is the first step to dismantling the whyte supremacist system and fighting for true equity for all. [classism =/= racism

‚Ä¢ acknowledging your whyte privilege means understanding that the entire system is built by
column3: and upheld by the whyte community

column1: ;hot news preity zinta tulis surat terbuka , meminta maaf telah menyakiti perasaan orang terkait üòØ preity zinta , yang telah menerima reaksi balik untuk pandangannya tentang gerakan merilis pernyataannya tentang gerakan itu dan meminta maaf karena tidak sengaja melukai perasaan orang . dalam pernyataannya , bintang 'kal ho naa ho ' ini berkata , ‚Äú saya pendukung besar gerakan ini dan sangat disayangkan bahwa beberapa komentar saya diambil di luar konteks . saya mengakui bahwa setiap orang berada dalam posisi untuk melawan dan saya tidak ingin mengesampingkan para wanita yang telah dilecehkan '' . mengacu pada pengalaman sendiri , preity mengatakan bahwa itu juga terjadi padanya dan dia bereaksi dengan kuat . `` alasan saya mengatakan ini 'saya berharap sesuatu sepei ini akan terjadi pada saya , saya akan bereaksi terhadapnya dan banyak lapisan , ketika itu terjadi , saya bereaksi dan seluruh dunia melihatnya '' , katanya . gerakan yang dimulai di hollywood lebih dari setahun yang lalu , kini digerakkan di india setelah mantan aktris tanushree dutta menuduh bintang mainnya , patekar diduga melecehkan dia di set lokasi syuting 'horn ok pleassss ' pada tahun 2008. sejak itu , para wanita dari berbagai lapisan masyarakat , terutama media dan industri hiburan , telah menyamakan dugaan pelanggaran seksual terhadap subhash ghai , alok nath , vikas bahl , kailash kher , chetan bhagat , sajid khan , dan varun grover , diantara yang lain bahkan saat mereka semua membantah tuduhan itu . preity zinta selanjutnya akan terlihat dalam film tundanya , bhaiaji superhittt . film yang juga dibintangi sunny deol dan ameesha patel ini akan rilis jumat ini . üòâ eccanchronicle ollywoodnews ;[('hot'

that changed thank god. everyday i'm learning to appreciate the life i have and to be happy about the little things. of course you can't be happy all the time
column2: no one is especially with mental illness. but it really helped me to write down what makes me me happy. one of the things that make me happy is listening to music by my favorite artists.

column1: so on friday it was really easy for me to be happy
column2: because i saw one of my favorite singers live. his name is lewis capaldi and his music is incredible. it's really sad so i like to cry my eyes out listening to his music and then i feel so much better afterwards. i was so nervous when i met him after the concert but he's honestly such a sweetheart! we talked
column3: made selfies and a video and i was so fucking happy! it was a dream come true meeting him! please check him out if you like sad music like adele or sam smith ‚ô°

column2: it's okay. i've been there too. but i can promise you you'll see light and happiness in your future as well ‚ù§

column1: 35% of all women older than 15 years have experienced physical violence from a partner or some form of sexual violence. a culture of toxic masculinity contributes to this reality. objectification of women creates entitlement to their bodies: rape. painting women as emotional and less gifted in sciences devalues women‚Äôs intelligence and potential contribution to society: female selective foeticide. gender based violence is the symptom of gender roles and sexism in our society as it intersects with other forms of societal oppression (racism
column4: albeism etc.). men are vilified for challenging these stereotypes too.

column1: 135950;instagram;2018-11-25 18:05:29;FALSE;"it was a year ago today i left az with something heavy hanging on my heart and secrets that threatened to drive me mad. i told my father the day before and i dropped a huge elephant on him. seeing his heart break made me break. he never knew. he was one of the last pieces of the puzzle. i could see the conflictions of the past 15 years. he may have been absent part of my life but he gave me some logical advice and he was completely right. i made the decision to make a report the next day after phoning a friend because i didn't have it in me to do it alone. also
column2: intuition told me she was someone i could trust and count on with this. it was the hardest thing i've ever done
column3: but i'm so grateful that i wasn't alone. it was also an almost 10 year weight off of my chest. within a few weeks i saw an investigator
column5: and had to dive deep to find strength i didn't know i had. it was a mess at first and even more so when i decided to tell my mother the truth over a month after the report. the dominoes fell after that. that's when i really found my strength. after months of waiting
column6: the investigation went to a close. there was nothing they could do and everyone i had grown up with had turned their backs. i felt truly alone in that moment. last march
column10: and told my mother not to contact me. i refused to continue living the way i had all my life. it was that revelation that drove me for the next few months. then
column11: i took on too much this fall and more dominoes came down. however
column12: i learned so much about myself. although there were a lot of failures
column13: i'm proud to say how far i've come over the past year. i didn't do it alone and i realized who all was really on my side and i'm so grateful to the select few who are.

column1: i'm excited to see what the future holds and i hope i can find that same strength i had again.
